p73
aVThe problems, actually, for this kind of case
p74
aVcome manyfold from decades of scientific research
p75
aVinvolving human memory.
p76
aVFirst of all, we have all the statistical analyses
p77
aVfrom the Innocence Project work,
p78
aVwhere we know that we have, what,
p79
aV250, 280 documented cases now where people have
p80
aVbeen wrongfully convicted and subsequently exonerated,
p81
aVsome from death row, on the basis of later DNA analysis,
p82
aVand you know that over three quarters of all of those cases
p83
aVof exoneration involved only eyewitness identification
p84
aVtestimony during the trial that convicted them.
p85
aVWe know that eyewitness identifications are fallible.
