aa(lp87
VThe other comes from an interesting aspect
p88
aVof human memory that's related to various brain functions
p89
aVbut I can sum up for the sake of brevity here
p90
aVin a simple line:
p91
aVThe brain abhors a vacuum.
p92
aVUnder the best of observation conditions,
p93
aVthe absolute best,
p94
aVwe only detect, encode and store in our brains
p95
aVbits and pieces of the entire experience in front of us,
p96
aVand they're stored in different parts of the brain.
p97
aVSo now, when it's important for us to be able to recall
p98
aVwhat it was that we experienced,
p99
aVwe have an incomplete, we have a partial store,
p100
aVand what happens?
p101
aVBelow awareness, with no requirement for any kind of
p102
aVmotivated processing, the brain fills in information
p103
aVthat was not there,
p104
aVnot originally stored,
p105
aVfrom inference, from speculation,
p106
aVfrom sources of information that came to you,
p107
aVas the observer, after the observation.
p108
aVBut it happens without awareness such that
p109
aVyou don't, aren't even cognizant of it occurring.
p110
aVIt's called reconstructed memories.
p111
aVIt happens to us in all the aspects of our life, all the time.
